I have tried to set it up with DI and Kernel, but exactly the same result. Works on Windows, not on Android.

**Expected behavior**
I expect it to just give a simple return string.

**Platform**
 - OS: Windows
 - IDE: Visual Studio
 - Language: C#
 - Source: NuGet package Microsoft.SemanticKernel 1.15.0

Differently from a normal data type, where properties can have a default value, when working with `VectorStoreGenericDataModel`, non nullable properties don't have the default .NET value (e.g. 0 for long) and cannot be defined with a default value either.

Example class:

```csharp
public class Custom
{
    [VectorStoreRecordKey(StoragePropertyName = "id")]
    public string Id { get; set; }

    [VectorStoreRecordVector(3)]
    public ReadOnlyMemory<float> Vec { get; set; }

    [VectorStoreRecordData(IsFilterable = true)]
    public int Count { get; set; }      // This has an implicit default of 0

    [VectorStoreRecordData(IsFilterable = true)]
    public int Count2 { get; set; } = 5;      // Explicit default of 5
}
```

**VectorStoreGenericDataModel** example code throwing an exception, because the `Count` value is not set:

```csharp
var db = new PostgresVectorStore(dataSource);

var def = new VectorStoreRecordDefinition
{
    Properties = new List<VectorStoreRecordProperty>
    {
        new VectorStoreRecordKeyProperty("Id", typeof(string)),
        new VectorStoreRecordVectorProperty("Vec", typeof(ReadOnlyMemory<float>)) { Dimensions = 3, DistanceFunction = DistanceFunction.CosineSimilarity },
        new VectorStoreRecordDataProperty("Count", typeof(long))
    }
};

var collection = db.GetCollection<string, VectorStoreGenericDataModel<string>>("tests", def);
await collection.CreateCollectionAsync().ConfigureAwait(false);

var record = new VectorStoreGenericDataModel<string>("1");
record.Vectors["Vec"] = new ReadOnlyMemory<float>([0.15f, 0.25f, 0.35f]);
await collection.UpsertAsync(record);
```

Exception:

> Microsoft.Extensions.VectorData.VectorStoreOperationException: Call to vector store failed.
> ---> Npgsql.PostgresException (0x80004005): 23502: null value in column "Count" of relation "tests" violates not-null constraint


The exception can be fixed changing `Count` to nullable `long?` or setting a value
```csharp
record.Data["Count"] = 123;
```

However, it would be better if

1. The property used .NET default, e.g. 0 in this case
2. The property could be configured with a default value, for instance:

```csharp
var def = new VectorStoreRecordDefinition
{
    Properties = new List<VectorStoreRecordProperty>
    {
        new VectorStoreRecordKeyProperty("Id", typeof(string)),
        new VectorStoreRecordVectorProperty("Vec", typeof(ReadOnlyMemory<float>)) { Dimensions = 3, DistanceFunction = DistanceFunction.CosineSimilarity },
        new VectorStoreRecordDataProperty("Count", typeof(long))
        {
            DefaultValue = 0,
        }
    }
};
```

In my scenarios, schemas are always built programmatically based on configuration or user input. This means collections cannot be strongly typed to a specific class. 
Currently, I use:

â†’ var collection = vectorStore.GetCollection<ulong, object>("name", definition);

Setting TRecord to object seems to work but feels hacky. A class extension to abstract/hide this would improve usability, something like this:

â†’ var collection = vectorStore.GetCollection<ulong>("name", definition);

comments.body:
@dluc I donâ€™t see how this actually works: at the end of the day, some databases support only Guids, others only strings, and yet others only ints - how could an abstraction (or decorator) allow the same code to be written against all three? At the end of the day, the code using IVectorStoreRecordCollection must pass in a specific type (Guid or int) that comes from somewhere; so even if we make the collection non-generic, code interacting with it would still have to be specialized per vector store, since it would need to provide the correct type.

As written elsewhere, the expectation to be able to write a single piece of code that just works on all connectors is unfortunately not something that can be achieved IMHO, simply because the databases themselves differ. We can do our best, but it's always going to be a leaky abstraction.

Having said that, we do have #10802 tracking improving dynamic usage around keys (i.e. the fact that VectorStoreGenericDataModel is generic over the key type).

> the expectation to be able to write a single piece of code that just works on all connectors is unfortunately not something that can be achieved IMHO

I don't think that's true, to me this is about choosing a good "default" in each implementation, rather than asking the user to "always" make a choice. Choosing the type of keys should be possible, but not mandatory.

Let's say one registers `IVectorStore` in the the service provider, assuming the app can substitute concrete implementations, for example using Qdrant during developent on localhost and using Azure AI Search in prod on Azure (or anything, this is just an example). 

The assumption won't work in a few scenarios, because the code is not portable (substitution not allowed). 

Here's an example (from https://github.com/microsoft/semantic-kernel/issues/10877) showing how the code will have to check against all the supported classes (aka leaky abstraction), requiring knowledge about each specific class:

```csharp
public async Task<IResult> CreateCollectionAsync(IVectorStore vectorStore, CreateCollectionRequest req, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // Record definition
    var properties = new List<VectorStoreRecordProperty>();
    foreach (var f in req.Fields)
    {
        switch (f.Type)
        {
            case FieldTypes.PrimaryKey:
                // More conditions needed here to support other storage engines (ulong keys, long, int, composite keys, etc)

                properties.Add(vectorStore is QdrantVectorStore     // <--------
                    ? new VectorStoreRecordKeyProperty(f.Name, typeof(Guid))
                    : new VectorStoreRecordKeyProperty(f.Name, typeof(string)));

                break;
            case FieldTypes.Vector:
                properties.Add(new VectorStoreRecordVectorProperty(f.Name, typeof(ReadOnlyMemory<float>))
                {
                    Dimensions = req.Dimensions,
                    DistanceFunction = req.DistanceFunction,
                    IndexKind = req.IndexKind
                });
                break;
            // ...
        }
    }
    var recordDefinition = new VectorStoreRecordDefinition { Properties = properties };

    // Create collection
    try
    {
        switch (vectorStore)                                // <--------
        {
            case QdrantVectorStore:                         // <--------
            {
                var collection = vectorStore.GetCollection<Guid, object>(req.CollectionName, recordDefinition);
                await collection.CreateCollectionAsync(cancellationToken).ConfigureAwait(false);
                break;
            }
            case AzureAISearchVectorStore:                  // <--------
            {
                var collection = vectorStore.GetCollection<string, object>(req.CollectionName, recordDefinition);
                await collection.CreateCollectionAsync(cancellationToken).ConfigureAwait(false);
                break;
            }
            case InMemoryVectorStore:                       // <--------
            {
                var collection = vectorStore.GetCollection<string, VectorStoreGenericDataModel<string>>(req.CollectionName, recordDefinition);
                await collection.CreateCollectionAsync(cancellationToken).ConfigureAwait(false);
                break;
            }
        }
    }
    catch (VectorStoreOperationException e)
    {
        // Qdrant + Azure AI Search                         // <--------
        if (e.InnerException?.Message.Contains("already exists", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase) == true)
        {
            this._log.LogError("Unable to create {StorageType} collection, it already exists", req.StorageType);
            return ...
        }

        // InMemory? (not throwing yet)
                                                            // <--------

        // More string matching for other storage engines
                                                            // <--------

        this._log.LogError(e, "Unable to create {StorageType} collection, unexpected error: {Message}", req.StorageType, e.Message);
        return ...
    }
}
```

